column168: On 11/01/2021 at 0158 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Maxwell Yard (Greenwood, SC)  discovered ETCX821050, a loaded tank car of Acetic Acid leaking from top of the car. The car was  isolated and the shipper, Mallinckrodt was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, responded  and found product on top of the tank car and observed where it leaked from around that manway..  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Kevin Byrd  919-878-7047. HEPACO removed the defective manway gasket and put a nozzle gasket on the tank  car. The tank car was released back into transportation without delay.
column169: (NAR code:209 5  What Failed: Manway, Hinged & Bolted  Where Failed: Connection between manway nozzle and manway cover  Why Failed: Gasket deteriorated )

column168: SequenceEvent: PACKAGE ARRIVED AT LEHI-182 FROM ORIGIN MILW-532 ON 10/29/21. HAZMAT RELOADED ONTO TRAILER XTRA 22725 ON 10/31/21. ARRIVED AT WAYN-74 AT 04:30. column168: Conductor noticed the odor of alcohol while switching car in the yard for delivery.   Switching stopped and cars in cut checked.  TILX 191736 was found to be dripping from the bottom outlet.  Bucket was placed under car and NS Haz Mat & contractor called.  Examination showed ethanol leaking from around the packing gland retainer on the bottom outlet valve stem.  Liquid was also seen in the threads of the bottom outlet nozzle.  Packing gland retainer and outlet cap were tightened and leak stopped.  Retainer was "cocked" on the valve shaft when found and once tightened, one side of the retainer now contacts the body of the valve.  Car needs to be shopped for replacement of packing and possible replacement of retainer.  Car held pending OTMA.

Patriot personnel arrived onsite at 1830 ET and confirmed approximately 10 gallons of product released to a 5' x 5' area of the trailer floor and a 2' x 2' area of the asphalt parking lot below. Contractors containerized the damaged drum into an 85 gallon metal overpack. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into a 55 gallon metal drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics Terminal XNW reported 20 gallons of UN1230 "MA-ST-HV" released on the dock from a 55 gallon metal drum that was punctured by a forklift. Terminal personnel flipped the drum to stop the release. ERTS dispatched Miller Environmental Group to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 0615 EST, Miller personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 30 gallons of product released to a 20' x 30' area of the concrete dock floor. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and collected into a 55 gallon metal drum. The damaged drum was placed into a 95 gallon poly overpack. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: During a routine compliance audit of the NS Williamson, WV yard, WV PUC Inspector David Miller heard a hissing sound from TILX 192927, residue last contained alcohols, n.o.s.  Mr. Miller climbed the car and determined the hissing sound to be coming from the manway area.  Car was switched out and isolated and a NS approved environmental contractor was called to respond.  Contractor found the manwy gasket to be old, distorted, and folded in on the sealing surface.  In addition, only one manway bolt was tool tight.  Gasket was replaced, manway properly secured, and car released.

column168: ANOTHER SERVICE CENTER EMPLOYEE BROUGHT PACKAGE INTO SERVICE CENTER BECAUSE THEY THOUGHT IT WAS JUST A TAPE JOB. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION THEY DISCOVERED IT WAS LEAKING AND NOTIFIED RESPONDER. RESPONDER SAW THAT PACKAGE CONTAINED AEROSOL CANS THAT WERE PLASTIC WRAPPED TOGETHER INSIDE A CARDBOARD BOX. THE PLASTIC WRAP WAS LABELED WITH A LIMITED QUANTITY DIAMOND WHILE THE OUTER BOX HAD NO MARKINGS. RESPONDER NOTIFIED RMP WHO OBTAINED REFERENCE NUMBER. ALL 12 CAPS OF THE AEROSOL CANS WERE DAMAGED AND ALL WERE PLACED IN THE AEROSOL CAN WASTE ACCUMULATION DRUM. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SOILED CARDBOARD AND PACKING MATERIAL WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: On November 12, 2021, facility personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers (RLC) location discovered two (2) boxes of batteries were damaged during transit. As a result, approximately one (1) gallon of battery acid released from one (1) damaged battery to the concrete loading dock surface. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to perform the necessary corrective action. AS personnel neutralized the free product, then collected all damaged and spent material into two (2) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal.

column168: On 11-9-21 at 1100 personnel in the CSXT Siebert Yard discovered WCHX 23121, a loaded tank  car of Pine Oil leaking from manway. The car was isolated and IFF Chemical Holdings were notified  (CHEMTREC Report #2021110900160). E3 Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was  dispatched to the scene and found product on the both sides of the tank car and product around  the manway and 4 of 6 manway swing bolts less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective  actions were communicated to the shipper Luke Moore at 706-799-7885. Contractor personnel l opened manway and found that gasket was in good working order, E3 Environmental cleaned the  product from the sides of the car and properly tool tightened the manway swing bolts. The leak  was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching  move.

column168: At 1256 EST Landstar Inway contacted ERTS regarding a spill of a UN2922 "Corrosive liquid, toxic, n.o.s." It was reported that at least (1) 330-gallon tote was reported leaking in the trailer, ditch and the side of the road. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1815 EST E3 arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately 270 gallons of product was released over a span of 30 miles. Due to heavy rain the ETA onsite determined the material would not be recoverable. A vac truck was utilized to collect as much impacted rain water as possible. The remaining 5 gallons in the tote was also collected. The impacted trailer floor was cleaned and decontaminated. EnviroServe sprayed the impacted pallets with water and citric clean then wiped them down and used them for spacers while reloading the trailer. Once the trailer was reloaded and secured the unit departed site. Five 55-gallon poly drums containing impacted absorbents and debris were generated and the vac truck contained approximately 250-gallons of impacted rain water. All waste was taken for disposal by EnviroServe.

column168: Landstar Ranger contacted ERTS requesting services related to a 200-gallon release of non-regulated UN1866 "Easaqam 501" from a tote. The driver performed a quick maneuver to avoid an accident, causing the load to shift. As a result, a tote was damaged and discharged its contents in the trailer and on to asphalt and soil. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental-LTL to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 0725 EST E3 arrived and confirmed that approximately 275 gallons of product released to a 15' x 15' and 5' x 5' on soil and broken asphalt.  E3 confirmed the tote was punctured by a pallet, resulting in the release. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and all pallets were repalletized.  The impacted soil was hand dug with shovels was then placed into a roll off with all other waste. The site was secured with poly sheeting for future remediation.
RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPOND SHEET TO WHICH LED TO THE SPILL BEING BROUGHT BACK TO THE DMP CAGE TO BE PROCESSED.

At 0455  EST, XPO terminal LDA called in a spill of a UN2810 "Nadic Methyl Anhydride NMA Hardener" from a metal drum into the trailer due to a forklift puncture. ERTS dispatched Allied International Emergency (AIE) to conduct all cleanup. At 0800 EST, AIE personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 45 gallons of product released to a 28' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 16' x 10' area of the concrete lot under the trailer. The damaged 55 gallon drum was placed into a 95 gallon metal overpack. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected. The damaged pallets were also removed, cut up and containerized. All cleanup debris waste was containerized into (5) 55 gallon metal drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 0806 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (XML) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to unknown reasons, approximately 1 pound of Caustic Soda Micro Pearls (Hazardous - UN1823) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor. XPO requested a contractor out for cleanup and containment. ERTS dispatched HazChem to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1135 EST, HazChem personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4 pounds of product released to the trailer floor from (3) 50 pound paper bags. The damaged bags and released material were collected and containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: There was a report of an odor around this car and upon inspection it was found that the odor was coming from the flanged area between the nozzle and 12 bolt magnetic gauging device.  The air monitor picked up high readings by three bolts, but no bubbles from a Snoop solution were detected from this location.  There was also no pressure on the car and the shipper advised this car should return with pressure.  At the location of the high readings, three bolts were discolored and a quarter size spot of material was on the top of the car directly under the bolts.  There was no other evidences of a release.  All fittings were secured and seals applied.  Car was placed in HZ hold awaiting an MRU.

column168: The tank was observed to be leaking by Louisiana Haz Mat State Trooper in Monroe, LA. HMM Tom Robinson was called for a response. On 11/10/2021 at approximately 05:00 hours CST an FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector performed a regulatory compliance check of tank car GATX 225374 (Load / Sodium Hydroxide Solution, UN 1824; Class 8, PGIII) at the CN Glenn Yard (Joliet Subdivision) in Chicago, IL. The inspection revealed that the vapor valve was in the open position and its securement plug was not installed. There was visible product spillage within the protective housing. CN Response team responded and also found the vapor valve to be open and plug not installed. The railcar was properly secured, spilled product cleaned up and released back to transportation.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 14:15PM WE RESPONDED TO A PACKAGE THAT WAS EXTREMELY WARM TO THE TOUCH. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED (6) ALKALINE SIZE D BATTERIES THAT WERE LOOSE INSIDE A SMALLS BAG. THE BATTERIES WERE MAKING CONTACT WITH ONE ANOTHER CAUSING A THERMAL EVENT TO OCCUR. THERE WAS NO PHYSICAL FIRE OR CHARRING OCCURRING, BUT THE BATTERIES WERE HOT ENOUGH TO MELT THE PLASTIC SURROUNDING THE BATTERIES. THERE IS A CONSUMER TYPE BOX INSIDE THE SMALLS BAG THAT MOST LIKELY HOUSED THE BATTERIES INITIALLY. THE BATTERIES WERE NOT PACKED IN A MANNER TO PREVENT MOVEMENT THAT COULD LEAD TO SHORT CIRCUITING OR IN A WAY TO PREVENT AN EVENT FROM OCCURRING DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE PACKAGE WAS ACCEPTED IN THE AIR NETWORK AND HAD ALREADY FLOWN FROM STL TO SDF. THE WARM PACKAGE WAS THEN DISCOVERED DURING THE SORTING PROCESS AT THE LOUISVILLE, KY WORLDPORT FACILITY AT SDF. AN NRC REPORT WAS MADE PER 171.15, REPORT 1322633.

At 0205 ET, Christopher Sain notified ERTS of a cargo release at UPH. It was reported that 5 gallons of “spectrum ct 1300” were released from a 5 gallon DF due to improper loading.  The release occurred on the trailer. The spill has been contained.  ERTS informed the caller that because the spilled material is corrosive, ERTS is required to dispatch a contractor.  The caller said that the terminal has all the necessary resources to clean up the spill.  The caller said the terminal has previous experience with cleaning up corrosive spills.  The caller insisted that the terminal will clean up the spill and declined the contractor option.   ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and the caller determined that terminal personnel could clean the release with PPE available on site.  The damaged cargo and oil dri were put into a 35 gallon DF.

At 1127 ET Edgar Lee with XFW notified ERTS of an 8-gallon release of UN 1866 Desmodur 3390A BA/SN from a 55-gallon metal drum due to a forklift puncture, impacting the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and the terminal feels comfortable cleaning the release with PPE available on site. Oil Dri will be utilized to collect the spilled material. The waste and cleanup debris will be placed into a 65-gallon poly waste container. ERTS requested photos of the waste drum.

At 0827 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal XCV notified ERTS of a 1 ounce release of UN2078 Mondur TD 80 Grade B from an 8 pound cardboard box due to improper loading, impacting the dock and box. ERTS dispatched First Call to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. AT 1050 ET, contractors arrived onsite and located the package. The contractor advised the terminal already conducted clean up and overpacked the drum before contractor arrival. The contractor was able to provide photos and cleanup info. The was was placed into a 30 gallon metal drum and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column162: DIRECTOR OF COMPLIANCE AND REGULATORY AFFAIRS
column168: Employee Jonathan Cole is a bulk driver assigned to Area #7315 Clearwater but he was running a route in Area #7006 Tampa. He was confused on the different setup of the Tampa delivery hose. The bleeder for relieving liquid before disconnecting the hose is on the hose itself in Clearwater but in Tampa the hose does not have one. In Tampa the bleeder is on the fill valve on the bobtail. Jonathan Cole was confused and used a wrench to loosen what he thought was the bleeder on the truck fill valve.The part he was loosening was a plug and not a bleeder valve. The loosened part shot out under pressure and the leak occurred.       Due to the vapor propane leaking from the removed plug, the wind direction and the proximity to a road way the decision was made to call 911 to help control the surrounding area. The decision was also made to call the local truck manufacture and repair shop to help assist with obtaining the a part to help plug the threaded hole that was now missing its plug.       The local emergency responders closed E. Hanna avenue to limit traffic interference while the leaking threaded area was plugged off to stop the leak. The local roadway was closed for approximately thirty (30) minutes. The leak was plugged and stopped within approximately forty (40) minutes from when the initial leak occured.
column169: Lessons Learned will be generated to share with the regional team. Additional training will be given to all  employees in the area and region. We will also look to see if a bleeder valve can be added to the hose end in Tampa to eliminate the operational differences between the areas.

Crew applied absorbents to the affected area and inspected the other freight for damage and impact. Crew advised they collected spent absorbents into a 5 gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On November 3, 2021 at 1900 ET XPO Logistics XSX reported a cargo release containing AFCO 5250 cleaner from a 55 gallon poly drum. ERTS reviewed the SDS, with XPO, terminal determined that a contractor could need to conduct the cleanup. Environmental Services arrived onsite at 2230 ET  and confirmed approximately twenty (20)-gallons of product released affecting a 5’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and 15’ x 5’ area of the asphalt lot. Contractors collected and containerized the damaged drum into one (1) 95-gallons overpacked poly drum and all clean-up debris into two (2) 55-gallons poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The Veolia driver was inspecting his roll off box that contained a hazardous waste solid before loading it on his truck at Veolia's ten day intransit facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI.  He noticed liquid that liquid material  leaked out of the side of the roll off box.  The box appeared to show signs of corrosion on the side of the box due to aging which caused the leak.  The amount that leaked was estimated to be about 12 gallons. The NRC was notified of the release since the leaked material exceeded its RQ.
column169: New roll off boxes have been purchased to replace older, aging ones.  The presence of liquid in the waste has been addressed with the original generator of the material and the process generating this waste is being reassessed.  In addition, more absorbent will be added to the bottom of the roll off before the filtercake is added in the future to absorb any liquid that may settle out of the waste during transportation..

column168: On 11/03/2021 at approximately 10:00 AM, a Veolia employee entered the back of a box van to offload containers when he noticed a 275 gallon tote (IBC) of Waste Corrosive Liquids, Acidic, Inorganic wet around the bottom of the container near the bottom outlet valve. He requested assistance and transferred the contents of the tote into another tote.  Once the contents of the container were transferred, Veolia employees then sent the non-leaking tote (IBC) to the Stablex facility in Quebec, Canada so it could be offloaded and properly disposed of. The Veolia employee investigated the source of the leak and it was apparent that the leak was at the bottom outlet valve of the tote. The age of the tote was estimated to be about 7 years based on the UN specification markings. It is assumed that the corrosive liquids degraded and damaged the IBC and allowed liquid to leak out around the outlet valve. It is estimated that about 1/2 a liter of liquid leaked into the box van. No liquid made it outside of the box van and the liquid on the truck floor was cleaned up. The empty IBC was also sent for proper disposal at an authorized facility.
column169: Veolia will continue to monitor shipments from this customer as well as others to see if there are any additional issues and will also be more vigilant with any totes that appear to be in a degraded condition. In the future, similar totes (IBCs) in the same condition will not be shipped and will be required to be transferred to a tote (IBC) that is in good condition.

column168: Veolia was requested to pick up and transport hazardous waste at Teledyne.  During the loading process, an employee previously loaded a two 5 gallon jerican containers onto the truck.  He then utilized a forklift to load two 55 gallon open top drums which were on a pallet.  While the operator of the forklift was maneuvering the load, the pallet grazed one of the two 5 gallon poly jericans which caused a small pin size puncture resulting in a leak.  The employee did not initially notice the leak and the container leaked for roughly 10 minutes when the employee smelled an odor.  Roughly 0.5 gallons had leaked during that time span.   Once the spill was identified, the absorbent pads and oil dry was placed on the spilled material.  The container was transferred into a new container.
column169: Based on the incident investigation, it is determined that the employee should have loaded the pelletized 55 gallon drums first for this situation.  Veolia will review the incident with all hazmat employees at this location and will retrain them on proper loading procedures.

Tank car was connected to unloading skid at destination facility and was being actively unloaded.  The transfer was nearly completed when the operator observed vapor leak coming out of the ?? bleeder valve on the unloading hose fitting.  When the operator applied pressure to the bleeder valve handle it broke off the valve.  In a panic, the operator exited the unloaded skid and shut down the scrubber system.  The car then vented a mixture of vapor and HCL liquid.  There was an estimated 5 gallons of HCL released to the pavement.  A response contractor neutralized and cleaned up the spilled material.

column168: AT THE UPS FACILITY IN COLOGNE, GERMANY, A DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS FOUND VISIBLY LEAKING AND RELEASING A STRONG VINEGAR-LIKE SMELL INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. WHILE INSIDE THE AIR ULD WITH THE PACKAGE, AN EMPLOYEE INHALED VAPORS FROM THIS PACKAGE AND BEGAN EXPERIENCING PHYSICAL DISCOMFORT ALONG WITH IRRITATED MUCOUS MEMBRANES. AS A PRECAUTION THE EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED IN APPROXIMATELY 90-120 MINUTES. AFTER BEING RELEASED, THE EMPLOYEE RETURNED BACK TO WORK TO COMPLETE THE SHIFT. THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT DID RETRIEVE AND DISPOSE OF THE PACKAGE PER LOCAL PROCEDURES IN COLOGNE, GERMANY. WE HAVE LIMITED PHOTOS OF THE UNDECLARED PACKAGE AND CONTENTS. THE OUTER BOX DOES NOT BEAR ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELS. RESPONDER DETERMINED THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 6 X 1 LITER BOTTLES OF UN2789, ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL. THIS IS PACKAGE 5 OF A 24 PIECE SHIPMENT, BUT OTHER PACKAGES HAD ALREADY EXPORTED COLOGNE, GERMANY.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Our driver loaded Sulfuric Acid (SA) in FMI Miami. After completing all checks consistent with FMI Miami and BJ Cecil Trucking requirements, driver left the property en route to FMI Safford. Driver drove approximately 75 miles SE on US 70 where the driver stopped to make a left hand turn, heading East on Norton Rd. The liquid surging in tanker from the stop, caused the Pressure Relief Device (PRD) to activate which resulted in a small amount of SA released on to the roadway. Driver turned East on Norton Rd. for roughly 1 mile where driver was approaching the intersection of Norton Rd. and Reay Rd. Driver slowed and noticed a mist coming from tanker. Driver immediately pulled over to investigate and confirmed SA leaking from tanker.Emergency response was activated. Driver contained area and tanker. Driver discovered the leak originated from PRD valve and communicated to emergency response team. AZ DPS arrived onsite and made a report. The duration of the release is estimated to be less than two minutes. The only know release of acid occured on the stop sign of US-70 and Norton Rd. as well as where the driver ultimately stopped on Norton Rd., near Reay Rd. A total of <4 gallons released. In-house Emergency Crew arrived on site and saturated all areas, several times, where SA was released on to the roadway with water and soda ash. Tanker was also saturated and treated to neutralize SA. PRD Valve was removed and replaced with a new PRD valve by Emergency Crew. Driver was cleared to proceed to offload location, FMI Safford.  Per our RI:  The failed PRD valve was brought into our shop and bench tested. The result was the PRD failed due to a weak spring.
column169: Actions preventing recurrence of this issue has already been taken by the company. The PRD valve that failed was one of two devices installed on our tankers. The remaining tankers in our fleet have "Girard" PRD's. Our actions were to immediately pull the remaining "Betts" PRD and replace with our standard "Girard" PRD. All of our tankers will remain uniform with "Girard" PRD's moving forward. Recommendations for improvement to hazardous material transportation would be to use equipment/products that are proven to withstand the wear and tear of daily usage

column168: At 00:56 ET,  Landstar Express notified ERTS of a vehicle malfunction at mile marker 378 on I-75S.  The trailer brakes caught fire and the fire could not be extinguished before compromising the entire contents of the trailer.  Of the 5 products being shipped on the BOL obtained, there were 3,629-pounds of Greasecutter Plus (UN1824), Class 8, PGIII on the trailer. AOTC confirmed that some of this material was released, due to the jugs melting in the fire. The material impacted by the GREASECUTTER PLUS / UN1824, was segmented from the non-haz material. The non-haz material was placed into a roll-off bin. The nonhazardous liquids will be taken to Valdosta for solidification. The box truck contained hazardous waste and will remain staged on site in transit position waiting for profiling.

column168: On 11   16   21, the BNSF Intermodal Team at S. Seattle notified LARS of top   stack container JBHU 233946 that had arrived on the inbound Z   train that was observed to have been leaking a clear substance during train movement but was no longer actively leaking. The substance was found on the underside of the unit and the top and sides of the bottom   stack unit and smelled strongly of a paint/epoxy odor. US Ecology was contacted to respond/remediate and found a pallet of 7   gal buckets of UN1263 paint (hazardous) had one bucket on the bottom with corner damage and a small hole from which approximately 6.5 gal of product had leaked out.  US Ecology returned to SSE with a forklift and removed cargo from the unit to gain access to the leaking area. They were able to isolate the source of the leak as a metal pail of "Milesi" paint on the bottom layer of a pallet that had creased and split open at the bottom of the bucket, most likely from heavy cargo placed on top of the entire stack; it appears approximately 6.5   gal of paint had leaked out of the 7   gal bucket. USE completed cleanup and overpacked the leaking bucket, and the unit was re   loaded and released for outgate.

column168: TILX 350413 was found in the Albuquerque, NM yard leaking from the manway. Upon inspection, the leak was confirmed to be leaking from the manway. All of the manway swing bolts were beyond tool-tight. It took two men and a 48" pipe wrench to break the swing bolt loose. The gasket in the manway lid looked good, but cause of leak was most likely caused from overtightening of the swing bolts. The lid gasket was removed, a nozzle gasket was added and the swing bolts tool tightened.
column169: Shipper must ensure that the swing bolts are only tool-tightened and no more. This needs to be done to prevent future releases of hazardous materials in the future.(NAR:220)

column168: UTLX 204370 was found in the Denver yard to be leaking from the top of the car. Upon inspection by a BNSF responder, its was found to be leaking product from the bottom side of the liquid valve, around the threads.  The valve was tight, but once removed to inspect for sealant or tape on the threads, none was found.  The threads were then taped and the valve was tool-tightened.
column169: The shipper must ensure that the valves are properly sealed and tool-tightened to prevent future releases of hazardous materials.(NAR:270)

column168: GATX 224678 was found in the Belen, NM yard to be leaking propane. An odor was noted as well as icing on the protective housing. Upon inspection, the liquid valve was closed and the release was coming from the plug.  The plug was able to be tightened two full turns and leak was stopped.  After further inspection, it was confirmed that the valve was closed, but was still leaking.  The plug had some thread sealant applied and tool-tightened again, but there is still a very minute leak to car. The plug on the other liquid valve was also less than tool-tight.  Car will be transloaded where it sits.
column169: Shipper must ensure that valves are tested for proper operation and leak tested prior to releasing for transportation to prevent future release of hazardous materials. Secondary closures also need to have thread sealant and be tool-tightened.(NAR:119)

column168: At 19:36 ET, Landstar Ranger notified ERTS of a cargo release on I-55 going southbound by exit 140 in Atlanta Township, IL. It was reported that an unknown amount of UN3264 "Sulfuric Acid" was released from 3 Drums and a IBC tote due to unknown reasons. The release impacted soil, asphalt, and a ditch. No waterways or drains were affected. ERTS dispatched Environmental Solutions to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1900 ET, Environmental Solutions arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100 gallons of product released to a 46'x18' area of asphalt, soil and adjacent ditch. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into (6) 95-gallon metal drums containing impacted soil, absorbents and debris. A vacuum truck was then used to remove approximately 200-gallons of liquid from the ditch and will be transferred into overpacks.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE AREA SUPERVISOR IN SECTION-D. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED THE RESPONDER AT DOOR 28. HE ARRIVED WITHIN A MINUTE, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 2 PLASTIC 5 LITER JUGS OF THE NON-HAZARDOUS SECTION OF A 2-PART KIT WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING THE LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON(S). THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A DOUBLE CORRUGATED 2 BOX CONFIGURATION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: The on-scene crash investigation revealed that Vehicle 1 was stopped on the shoulder north of I-20. Vehicle 2 was traveling west on I-20 in the outside lane before the crash. The driver of Vehicle 1 began to enter the outside lane of I-20. As Vehicle 1 entered I-20, it was struck in the left rear by the front right of Vehicle 2. After impact, Vehicle 2 began to flip, causing the vehicle's roof to make contact with the trailer. Vehicle 2 then began a clockwise rotation and rotated one-quarter of a rotation before its final rest. Vehicle 2 came to its final rest in the middle of both westbound lanes facing northwest, 6.6 feet west of the impact area. Vehicle 1 came to its final rest partially on the north shoulder and outside lane of I-20 facing west, 72.2 feet west of the impact area. Scrapes on the roadway determined the impact area. The crash resulted in severe damage to the left rear of Vehicle 1's trailer. In addition, Vehicle 2 received severe damage to the front right, right side front, and center front. The drivers of both vehicles were restrained. All measurements taken are approximate.

column168: On 11/29/21, the BNSF Los Angeles IMF reported JBHU 262769 (Waybill Hazardous) as leaking a white   like substance along the container rail and puddling on the ground within the parking stall. On the behalf of the shipper, United Pumping was contacted and dispatched to complete inspection and any necessary remediation.  Inspection of the parking stall revealed approximately 10   15 gallons of product lost outside of the unit while Interior inspection revealed a palletized shipment to include IBC totes in a 2 X 2 offset pattern. Longitudinal and doorway securement was provided by the use of Tygard. The source of the leak was determined to be originating from a 330   gallon tote loaded with Corrosive Material carrying a class 8 UN 1824 placard. Approximately 50 gallons of the product were lost before the completion of the remediation. The cause of the leak was the result of failed packaging within the IBC tote which also resulted in contaminating cargo directly adjacent to the tote. As a result, the container required extensive cleaning on both the interior and exterior before allowing to out gate.
column169: Inspect packages before, during and after loading for potential damage.

column168: ESTES-Toledo (TOL) Terminal #92 reported 4-gallons of UN3265 "Corrosive liquid, acidic, organic, n.o,s" released on inside of the trailer, parking lot below, and drain catch basin from a 55-gallon plastic drum that was crushed due to a load shift. ERTS dispatched First Call Environmental (FCE) to conduct all onsite clean up operations. At 0855 EST FCE personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4 gallons of product released. Absorbents (soda ash) were worked into the impacted areas to solidify the free standing liquids and collected into six 55-gallon poly drums. The impacted pallets and debris were containerized into one 95-gallon poly overpack. The damaged drum was also placed into a 95-gallon overpack. All waste was staged onsite.

Ward Trucking released a hazardous, UN1760, Corrosive Liquid, 8, PG III release inside of a trailer at a customer location. The 55-gallon poly drum fell over causing the release. Approximately 20-gallons of product has released to the trailer floor and the ground below. The ground below has been contained with absorbent booms. At 1657 ET, Sustain dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup operations. The trailer floor has been impacted along with a 10” x 25’ area outside of the trailer on the ground. Approximately 15-gallons or less was released. EnviroServe personnel are using a neutralizing agent and water to clean and neutralize the release. The damaged drum is being plugged and over-packed.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling, a single vehicle accident resulted in the tank truck rolling over onto its side. Local Fire Department responded to assess the site. Tanker was in tact, however, offload was required to upright vehicle. HERR, Inc. was contacted to perform cleanup of potential release, and Hepaco was dispatched to offload the tanker. A recovery truck was called in by Pope Transport, and Hepaco offloaded the tanker without further incident. Approximately 15 gallons of diesel fuel were released from the saddle tank cap, and approximately 5 gallons of gasoline were released from the dome cover while tank was on its side. Upon completion of offload, HERR, Inc. used a vacuum truck to remove the residual from the tanker. HERR, Inc. returned the following day to excavate the impacted soil along the road shoulder. Approximately 2 tons of contaminated soil and 100 gallons of free product were transported to HERR, Inc. of Whiteville, NC for disposal. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Pope Transport will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: While picking up waste from the client, the involved employee placed two, 1-gallon cans of waste paint colorant on top of the cubic yard box instead of packaging the cans inside of the cubic yard box for transport. Then, while attempting to transfer the client waste to the Ingenium trailer, the employee failed to recognize that the truck's lift gate was not level and pushed the cubic yard box with the cans atop onto the lift gate. This action resulted in the pallet jack shifting which in tum, caused the waste colorant cans to fall, one of which released its contents. The employee immediately obtained assistance and took appropriate measures to contain the spill. The released material was promptly removed from the parking lot surface. At no time did any spilled material reach any storm drains. The spilled material was appropriately packaged into a cubic yard box for transport and the generator was notified of the incident.   As a result of Ingenium's internal investigation, it was determined that the involved employee was a trainee who acted, of their own accord, outside of their current level of training.
column169: After a thorough internal investigation, Ingenium's Corrective Action Team issued the following corrective actions to prevent a recurrence:   1. The involved employee was counseled regarding the the proper preparation of waste containers for transport, the proper movement of waste from the client site to the Ingenium trailer, the proper procedures for utilizing mechanical assistance devices, and the proper process for loading waste onto the trailer.   2. Operations employees refresher training for the above mentioned aspects of waste pick-up was conducted by Ingenium's EHS professionals.   3. New employee onboarding and training procedures were reviewed and recommendations for improvement were implemented.

column168: On 11/30/2021, at approximately 0800, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee # 3729714 at the station location in Des Moines, reporting an undeclared dangerous goods spill. The shipments consisted of 8 fiberboard boxes, each containing 2 plastic bottles. One of the packages showed evidence of spillage, garnering the attention to the agent. The inner bottles show spillage around the tops of each containers. Further investigation revealed that the shipment contained 2 10-kg bottles of stereolithography resin, classified as UN3032, Environmentally Hazardous Substances, liquid. The package was prepared per IATA Regualtions. The package also shows two areas cut out in the shape of diamonds, suggesting that the hazard labels had been removed from the package. The shipment is being held for an FAA investigation.

The material was picked up on November 10, 2021 by Clean Earth as part of a sub-contracted milk run transport from the generator's facility at 625 W. Illinois Avenue, Aurora, Il. It was held at a 10-day in-transit location in Gary, Indiana. On November 12, 2021, Clean Earth stopped at the R3 Environmental Management facility in Elgin, Illinois (with the IBC on board), then proceeded to the DS Container facility at 1789 Hubbard Ave., Batavia Illinois. During the transport from Gary, IN and at the stop in Elgin, Illinois, no sign of failure of the tote or release of material was noted. When the shipment stopped at the Batavia, IL location, the driver discovered that material was actively Ieaking from an approximately 6 inch long crack in the bottle of the IBC Some of the release material escaped from the vehicle and pooled in an area of asphalt pavement beside the vehicle. Plastic sheeting and vermiculite was initially used to control the spread of the material that had exited the vehicle. A hazardous material response contractor(HazChem Environmental Corporation, Addison, IL) was contacted to assist in clean-up of the incident. At 1043 notification was made to 911 dispatch,. At 1100 the Batavia Fire Department arrived on the scene. At 1135 a representative of the Batavia Water Department arrived and confirmed that no surface water or surface water conveyances had been impacted by the release. At 1150, HazChem arrived on site and under the direction of R3 Environmental, commenced with clean-up. Clean-up entailed neutralization of spilled waste, collection of contaminated debris, transfer of remaining waste in the failed tote to a new tote, dismantlement of the old tote for disposal, and pressure washing the affected asphalt area. The pressure wash water was also collected for disposal.

column168: On 19 Nov 22, Landstar notified ERTS of a cargo release at 4512 Clover Dr, Clemmons, NC. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to the address the spill that was observed on the trailer floor. It was reported that approximately 1 pint of product UN1789 Hydrochloric acid residue released into trailer #694055 while filling totes at a customer's location. Area impacted measured 1ft by 1ft of the trailer floor. No cargo was on the trailer when the contractor arrived to address the spill. The spill was addressed via Neutralization and pH tested to confirm neutralization.  A single 55-gallon drum of waste (absorbent powder and pads) was generated to address this spill.  The waste was transported off site until proper disposal was arranged.

On 21 Nov 22, Landstar called ERTS to request spill response for a UN1993 Limonene release inside trailer #694155 in Amarillo, TX.  Upon arrival at the staged trailer location, the responding contractor assessed the trailer contents and observed a single pint leak from plumbing at the bottom of a single metal tote that affected a 2ft-by-2ft area of the trailer floor. The responding contractor placed the tote on poly sheeting and then tightened the components observed on the aforementioned plumbing and no additional leakage was evident. The trailer flooring was subsequently addressed with absorbents, and no additional media was affected. Hepaco generated one 55-gallon metal drum of waste which the contractor departed the site with for proper disposal. Final disposal was on 29 Nov 21 at Southwest Landfill and Canyon, Tx.

column168: On 11/10/2021, at approximately 0800, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee # 294822 at the ramp facility in Anchorage, reporting a hazardous spill. The shipment consists of 6- 1 liter bottles in one fiberboard box. One of the bottles leaked, due to a lost cap. The spillage affected several other packages. Further research revealed that the shipment was undeclared drain cleaner, being void of the IATA-required markings and labeling. The remainder of the shipment was placed in a salvage drum and awaits an FAA investigation.
